00:14:54.020 --> 00:14:55.520
what they have in front of them.

00:14:55.520 --> 00:14:57.500
Why is it so difficult to see? Yeah,

00:14:57.500 --> 00:15:00.020
- It's, it's one of these
things I think sometimes it's,

00:15:00.020 --> 00:15:01.850
it's very, it's very human.

00:15:01.850 --> 00:15:06.320
You know, we, we, we wanna
deal with a world that we want

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:09.620
to see and we are not
dealing in a world which it

00:15:09.620 --> 00:15:10.790
actually exists.

00:15:10.790 --> 00:15:11.930
Remember that diplomacy

00:15:11.930 --> 00:15:14.900
and foreign policy is, is is never static.

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:16.040
There's no end state.

00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:17.600
You know, we're not gonna end up

00:15:17.600 --> 00:15:20.360
with the fantastic world government.

00:15:20.360 --> 00:15:21.740
It's always diplomacy

00:15:21.740 --> 00:15:23.600
and trying to work in
different directions.

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:27.920
Right now, the pendulum is
going to towards transaction,

00:15:27.920 --> 00:15:32.360
towards nationalism,
towards bilateral relations.

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:34.400
And at some stage it'll
start swinging back.

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:36.710
But when it starts, we have to make sure

00:15:36.710 --> 00:15:38.300
that everyone feels
that they're part of it.

00:15:41.300 --> 00:15:44.540
- The golden age of
America begins right now.

00:15:44.540 --> 00:15:48.980
I will very simply put America first.

00:15:51.860 --> 00:15:54.650
We are at the start of a thrilling new era

00:15:54.650 --> 00:15:56.270
of national success.

00:15:57.170 --> 00:16:01.485
Sunlight is pouring over the
entire world. We'll be told

00:16:01.485 --> 00:16:04.010
- That it's xenophobic, we'll be told

00:16:04.010 --> 00:16:05.120
that it's small minded.

00:16:14.270 --> 00:16:16.310
- Do you worry about
society splintering the

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:17.480
rise of populism?

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:18.980
The, yeah, definitely not being

00:16:18.980 --> 00:16:20.210
able to talk to each other anymore.

00:16:20.210 --> 00:16:21.260
- Yeah, I mean, what we have

00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:23.660
to avoid is the polarization of society.

00:16:23.660 --> 00:16:26.630
We have now the technological
instruments to polarize

00:16:26.630 --> 00:16:28.370
as much as we can because we can kind

00:16:28.370 --> 00:16:32.390
of start living in not only
al alternative realities,

00:16:32.390 --> 00:16:34.040
but in alternative truths.

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:36.560
And that's very dangerous for democracy

00:16:36.560 --> 00:16:39.650
because if you don't
have basic agreement of

00:16:39.650 --> 00:16:42.050
what facts are say on science or

00:16:42.050 --> 00:16:45.770
otherwise, then you cannot
have a democratic discourse.

00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:47.540
And, and we have to try to avoid that.

00:16:47.540 --> 00:16:50.540
We're seeing some of it
obviously in the United States,

00:16:50.540 --> 00:16:52.190
but it's not only the United States.

00:16:52.190 --> 00:16:54.440
We're seeing it in many
other liberal democracies.

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:55.610
Finland is a small country.

00:16:55.610 --> 00:16:58.070
We can't ev you know, we can't have that.

00:16:58.070 --> 00:17:00.290
- Is Europe prepared to go to war?

00:17:00.290 --> 00:17:03.320
- Well, I mean, our mentality is that

00:17:03.320 --> 00:17:04.340
the better you prepare,

00:17:04.340 --> 00:17:07.520
the less likely you're
gonna end up in, in a war.

00:17:08.570 --> 00:17:11.180
- Finland has a larger
artillery than France

00:17:11.180 --> 00:17:14.210
and Germany combined,
despite being a small country

00:17:14.210 --> 00:17:15.560
with a fraction of the German

00:17:15.560 --> 00:17:19.220
and French population per capita.

00:17:19.220 --> 00:17:22.310
Finland ranks seventh
in the world in total

00:17:22.310 --> 00:17:24.350
military personnel number.

00:17:24.350 --> 00:17:26.570
- We have obligatory military service,

00:17:26.570 --> 00:17:28.910
so 900,000 men and
women that have done it.

00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:33.910
My son just finished his,
I did mine in 1988 and 89.

00:17:34.040 --> 00:17:35.480
We have 280,000

00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:38.210
that we can put out at
wartime from reserves.

00:17:38.210 --> 00:17:42.620
We have 62 F eighteens, we
have long range mass cells,

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:46.520
land C and air, we just
bought 64 F 30 fives.

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:48.770
We have the biggest artillery
together with Poland.

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:51.690
And as I always say, we don't have them

00:17:51.690 --> 00:17:53.580
because we're worried about Stockholm.

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:56.100
And our argument is that
the better you're prepared,

00:17:56.100 --> 00:17:57.450
the less likely you're end up.

00:17:57.450 --> 00:17:59.400
- But the rest of Europe is not prepared.

00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:01.230
- Well, I think many of them are,

00:18:01.230 --> 00:18:02.700
and many of them are waking up.

00:18:02.700 --> 00:18:05.610
We are increasing our
preparedness in order

00:18:05.610 --> 00:18:06.660
to avoid the worst.

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:08.160
- I mean, I'm sure you have
good days and bad days.

00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:10.020
What do you do on a bad day to, to try

00:18:10.020 --> 00:18:12.600
and work things through on to
try and keep a level headed?

00:18:12.600 --> 00:18:15.090
- I mean, one, you have to be
really well prepared yourself.

00:18:15.090 --> 00:18:17.970
So I spend my early morning
hours from about five

00:18:17.970 --> 00:18:20.070
to eight going through material

00:18:20.070 --> 00:18:23.580
and reading to make sure that
I'm, you know, on the ball.

00:18:23.580 --> 00:18:26.700
And then secondly, you have
to have a team which is able

00:18:26.700 --> 00:18:29.940
to inform you about every
little minute detail and,

00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:33.540
and keep you all the
time ahead of the curve.

00:18:33.540 --> 00:18:36.180
And then number three,
you have to calm down.

00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:37.590
You know, you have to understand

00:18:37.590 --> 00:18:40.530
that the world is not gonna
be finished in the six years I

00:18:40.530 --> 00:18:44.550
I'm in this office, or 12 years
depending on if I run again.

00:18:44.550 --> 00:18:47.785
You just have to take it day
by day and, and, and, and, and,

00:18:47.785 --> 00:18:51.275
and try to, you know, solve
small crisis and big crisis.

00:18:51.275 --> 00:18:52.980
- What, what do you learn from sports

00:18:52.980 --> 00:18:54.105
that you bring to politics?

00:18:54.105 --> 00:18:57.570
- You, you probably
learn to cut your losses

00:18:57.570 --> 00:19:00.030
and actually to accept failure

00:19:00.030 --> 00:19:01.320
because in life you're gonna go

00:19:01.320 --> 00:19:03.270
through moments when you fail and,

00:19:03.270 --> 00:19:05.220
and you know, then you either learn

00:19:05.220 --> 00:19:06.690
something from it or you don't.

00:19:06.690 --> 00:19:10.650
And from indoor sports, you
just learn how to grind it out.

00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:13.170
So sports, I have to admit,
has always helped me.

00:19:13.170 --> 00:19:15.180
It's, it's a big part of who I am.

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:17.400
- Yeah. And, and you famously
said that actually one hour

00:19:17.400 --> 00:19:20.310
of sports or exercise gives
you two hour of energy.

00:19:20.310 --> 00:19:21.720
Do we need to normalize that more?

00:19:21.720 --> 00:19:23.340
- Well, normalize is difficult

00:19:23.340 --> 00:19:25.710
because I never wanna be
judgemental about anyone

00:19:25.710 --> 00:19:27.210
else's lifestyle.

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:31.080
So I've been able to lead a
life whereby it's been possible

00:19:31.080 --> 00:19:32.610
for the past 20, 30 years.

00:19:32.610 --> 00:19:34.800
And I think it's a lot about habits

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:37.050
and then suddenly they
almost become an addiction.

00:19:37.050 --> 00:19:39.120
You have to be a, a little bit careful,

00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:41.670
but I, I'd say that I'm
probably a better person

00:19:41.670 --> 00:19:43.170
for doing one hour of exercise,

00:19:43.170 --> 00:19:45.210
albeit today I've only done half an hour.

00:19:45.210 --> 00:19:47.460
- And what have you had to adapt
since you become president?

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:50.460
- I think there's certain
behavioral patterns.

00:19:50.460 --> 00:19:54.330
You know, you have to perhaps
hide your personality a little

00:19:54.330 --> 00:19:55.625
bit, not too much.

00:19:55.625 --> 00:19:59.280
But the reason I do it is that
I respect the institution.

00:20:00.120 --> 00:20:03.000
You know, I'm the 13th president
of the Republic of Finland.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:06.660
I understand the historic
gravitas of the task.

00:20:06.660 --> 00:20:08.520
So that means that, you know,

00:20:08.520 --> 00:20:12.810
I can't in every public situation
be just the good old Alex.

00:20:12.810 --> 00:20:15.960
I can do that with my friends,
I can do that with my family,

00:20:15.960 --> 00:20:17.310
I can do it with my staff.

00:20:17.310 --> 00:20:19.260
But there are certain
elements of, of the job

00:20:19.260 --> 00:20:21.000
that you just have to play the role.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.360
- But leaders also connect
through personalities. Yes.

00:20:24.360 --> 00:20:27.210
How has that helped with
President Trump? President Xi?

00:20:27.210 --> 00:20:29.880
- Well, I mean, it helps with
everyone to a certain extent.

00:20:29.880 --> 00:20:33.150
I, I think diplomacy is
really about two things.

00:20:33.150 --> 00:20:35.310
It's about state relations

00:20:35.310 --> 00:20:38.130
and then it's about personal
relations and connections.

00:20:38.130 --> 00:20:41.100
And then I think it's my job
to try to connect with people

00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:44.460
and, and I, I hope I, I hope
I succeed sometimes, you know,

00:20:44.460 --> 00:20:48.370
I, when I was with President
Xi, I felt we had a very good

00:20:48.370 --> 00:20:50.710
and respectful conversation
when I was playing

00:20:50.710 --> 00:20:51.970
golf with President Trump.

00:20:51.970 --> 00:20:53.260
We had a really good time.

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:55.030
- What was President Trump like

00:20:55.030 --> 00:20:56.140
on the golf course? He played

00:20:56.140 --> 00:20:57.140
- For pleasure for eight hours.

00:20:57.140 --> 00:20:58.540
Very, very, yeah, very talkative.

00:20:58.540 --> 00:21:01.240
You know, golf is a nice social setting.

00:21:01.240 --> 00:21:03.100
And again, going back to my dad,

00:21:03.100 --> 00:21:05.110
I remember my dad being very encouraging

00:21:05.110 --> 00:21:07.810
and saying, you know, Alex,
even if you don't become a golf

00:21:07.810 --> 00:21:10.810
professional, golf will
be useful for you one day.

00:21:10.810 --> 00:21:12.760
And I was going, yeah, sure dad.

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:14.650
And sure enough, there
I was on the first tee

00:21:14.650 --> 00:21:16.990
with President Trump and you
know, I I had a good time.

00:21:16.990 --> 00:21:19.390
And it doesn't, you know, the
fact that you have a good time

00:21:19.390 --> 00:21:20.980
with someone doesn't
mean they agree with him,

00:21:20.980 --> 00:21:22.870
especially coming from a small country.

00:21:22.870 --> 00:21:26.290
What you wanna do is,
is you wanna, you know,

00:21:26.290 --> 00:21:28.150
nudge things in the right direction.

00:21:28.150 --> 00:21:30.520
And that means that
you have conversations,

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:32.980
which sometimes can be
difficult and awkward.

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:34.270
Sometimes they can be good.

00:21:34.270 --> 00:21:37.150
And, and, and then, you
know, the rest of it is, is,

00:21:37.150 --> 00:21:38.230
is about getting results.

00:21:38.230 --> 00:21:40.540
And I hope I get results
with my diplomacy,

00:21:40.540 --> 00:21:42.280
- But I if you have a
good time, does it mean

00:21:42.280 --> 00:21:43.960
that they listen to your arguments more?

00:21:43.960 --> 00:21:45.155
- I dunno, you have to ask them,

00:21:45.155 --> 00:21:46.900
- What, what do you,
what did you learn about

00:21:46.900 --> 00:21:48.160
him? I mean, is he different?

00:21:48.160 --> 00:21:49.540
- Actually, you know, this is the thing,

00:21:50.530 --> 00:21:52.750
and I've always said
this, that funnily enough,

00:21:52.750 --> 00:21:54.850
and I hadn't really
played golf for 35 years.

00:21:54.850 --> 00:21:56.410
I mean, when I quit, I quit.

00:21:56.410 --> 00:21:59.020
So, but I've always said it,

00:21:59.020 --> 00:22:01.540
you learn about the personality

00:22:01.540 --> 00:22:04.690
of a human being on the
first hole of a golf course.

00:22:04.690 --> 00:22:07.600
You see if they're edgy,
if they're impatient,

00:22:07.600 --> 00:22:10.660
if they're frustrated, if
they're fun, if they're relaxed.

00:22:10.660 --> 00:22:13.570
And I have to say, I had no
uncomfortable moments during

00:22:13.570 --> 00:22:16.720
that round, and we hit
good shots and bad shots.

00:22:16.720 --> 00:22:18.370
So, you know,

00:22:18.370 --> 00:22:20.680
people are quite different
in a golf course. Sometimes

00:22:20.680 --> 00:22:22.930
- You, you seem to have a quite glamorous

00:22:22.930 --> 00:22:24.040
life from the outside.

00:22:24.040 --> 00:22:25.660
What do people not know?

00:22:25.660 --> 00:22:28.060
- What I keep on telling
people who say, oh, you met

00:22:28.060 --> 00:22:29.680
that person, you met that person,

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:30.970
and you sat next to that one.

00:22:30.970 --> 00:22:34.030
I said, listen, they're
just normal human beings.

00:22:34.030 --> 00:22:37.630
See, the thing is that in today's world

00:22:37.630 --> 00:22:41.110
with modern technology, you
create an image of a human being

00:22:41.110 --> 00:22:44.680
who you've never met because
you've seen them on social

00:22:44.680 --> 00:22:48.850
media or TV or whatever, and it's normal.

00:22:48.850 --> 00:22:53.680
But the truth is that
no human being is as bad

00:22:53.680 --> 00:22:55.720
as they look in the public eye,

00:22:55.720 --> 00:22:58.150
nor as good as they
look in the public eye.

00:22:58.150 --> 00:23:00.220
And most people that I met
throughout my life are just

00:23:00.220 --> 00:23:01.300
normal human beings.

00:23:01.300 --> 00:23:03.100
They like to talk about normal stuff.

00:23:03.100 --> 00:23:06.520
I'll tell you, one of
the highlights of my term

00:23:06.520 --> 00:23:11.290
so far was a private dinner
with President Zelensky

00:23:11.290 --> 00:23:14.470
and Zelensky and my wife Suan

00:23:14.470 --> 00:23:19.150
at our home in our flat
with no one else around.

00:23:19.150 --> 00:23:21.940
We were just chatting
there, drinking wine,

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:25.300
talking about family,
and talking about life.

00:23:25.300 --> 00:23:27.700
And you have to understand
that even someone like Flo

00:23:27.700 --> 00:23:32.350
Zelensky who's gone through
a war that no one wanted,

00:23:32.350 --> 00:23:33.970
and he, the least of it,

00:23:33.970 --> 00:23:36.400
is a normal human being.
There's no glamor in that

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:38.980
- Present. Stu, thank you so much.

00:23:38.980 --> 00:23:39.250
- Thank you.

